<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-03-part2">
  <title>Module 2: The Transpose and Matrix Powers</title>
  
  <introduction>
    <objectives>
      <title>Topics and Objectives</title>
      <p>We will explore the following concepts in this section:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>the transpose of a matrix</p></li>
        <li><p>matrix powers</p></li>
        <li>
            <p>apply the matrix transpose and matrix powers to solve and analyze matrix equations</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>Objectives: Students should be able to apply the matrix transpose and matrix powers to solve and analyze matrix equations.</p>
    </objectives>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-matrix-transpose">
    <title>The Transpose of a Matrix</title>
    <p>
      <m>A^T</m> is the matrix whose columns are the rows of <m>A</m>.
    </p>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-transpose-compute">
      <title>Example: Computing a Transpose</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute <me>\begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \end{pmatrix}^T</me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <me>\begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 2 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp 0 \\ 4 \amp 2 \end{pmatrix}</me>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <assemblage xml:id="properties-transpose">
      <title>Properties of the Matrix Transpose</title>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li><p><m>(A^T)^T = A</m></p></li>
          <li><p><m>(A + B)^T = A^T + B^T</m></p></li>
          <li><p><m>(rA)^T = rA^T</m></p></li>
          <li><p><m>(AB)^T = B^T A^T</m></p></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </assemblage>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-matrix-powers">
    <title>Matrix Powers</title>
    <p>
      For an <m>n \times n</m> matrix and positive integer <m>k</m>, <m>A^k</m> is the product of <m>k</m> copies of <m>A</m>:
      <me>A^k = AA \dots A</me>
    </p>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-matrix-power">
      <title>Example: Compute <m>C^2</m></title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>C = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix}</m>. Compute <m>C^2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <me>C^2 = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix}</me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-comprehensive-example">
    <title>Dimension Analysis Example</title>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>Define:</p>
        <me>
          A = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{pmatrix}, \quad 
          B = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 8 \end{pmatrix}, \quad 
          C = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \end{pmatrix}
        </me>
        <p>Which of these operations are defined, and what are the dimensions of the result?</p>
        <p>
          <ol label="1">
            <li><p><m>A + 3C^2</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>A(AB)^T</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>A + ABCB^T</m></p></li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol label="1">
            <li><p>Undefined. <m>A</m> is <m>2 \times 2</m> while <m>C</m> is <m>3 \times 3</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Defined. Result is <m>2 \times 3</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Defined. Result is <m>2 \times 2</m>.</p></li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <summary>
    <p>
      In this section, we used the matrix transpose and matrix powers to solve and analyze equations. We can now determine whether a particular expression involving matrices is defined and what the resulting dimensions will be.
    </p>
  </summary>
</section>